## General Guidelines

1. **Always check `@components` first** before creating UI components
2. **Use consistent styling** - Components follow design system
3. **Accessibility** - Components include proper ARIA attributes
4. **Type safety** - All components are fully typed
5. **Composition** - Combine components instead of creating new ones
6. **Error handling** - Use ErrorBoundary for error-prone components

---

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

❌ **DON'T**: Create custom button components
```typescript
// BAD
const MyButton = ({ onClick, children }) => (
    <button onClick={onClick} className="my-button">
        {children}
    </button>
);

// GOOD
import { Button } from "@components";
<Button onClick={onClick}>{children}</Button>
```

❌ **DON'T**: Create custom text styling
```typescript
// BAD
<div style={{ fontSize: "1rem", fontWeight: "bold" }}>Text</div>

// GOOD
import { BaseText } from "@components";
<BaseText size="md" weight="bold">Text</BaseText>
```

❌ **DON'T**: Create custom cards
```typescript
// BAD
<div className="my-card" style={{ padding: "1em", background: "..." }}>
    Content
</div>

// GOOD
import { Card } from "@components";
<Card>Content</Card>
```

❌ **DON'T**: Skip error boundaries
```typescript
// BAD
<MyComponent /> // No error handling

// GOOD
import ErrorBoundary from "@components/ErrorBoundary";
<ErrorBoundary>
    <MyComponent />
</ErrorBoundary>
```

❌ **DON'T**: Create custom form controls
```typescript
// BAD
<input type="checkbox" checked={value} onChange={e => setValue(e.target.checked)} />

// GOOD
import { FormSwitch } from "@components";
<FormSwitch title="Enable" value={value} onChange={setValue} />
```

---

## When to Create New Components

Only create new components if:
1. The functionality doesn't exist in `@components`
2. It's a plugin-specific component that won't be reused
3. It's a complex composite component unique to your plugin
4. You've confirmed no similar component exists

If you create a new component:
- Follow existing component patterns
- Use existing utilities (`classNameFactory`, `classes`, etc.)
- Include proper TypeScript types
- Add error boundaries if needed
- Consider contributing it back if reusable
